The Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton — This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first edition of J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series — Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (known as Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the United States) — at literary festivals and bookstores. They have ample reason to do so.
Since the young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "boy who lived" has become a symbol of resilience and endurance.
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, translated into 70 languages, and sold a combined total of 450 million copies.
The eight films based on the book have earned a cumulative $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional $7 billion in revenue.
For readers of a certain age and with a literary mindset, it is hard to imagine a day when global audiences were not captivated by Rowling's works.
Therefore, I am always amazed to recall how my students reacted poorly to Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone when I included it in the syllabus of my popular literature course at Princeton University in the fall of 1999. Since 1993, I have been teaching a course on "Bestsellers in America."
This course examines popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to consider why and in what ways these bestsellers attract their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask students to choose a final work that represents popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, the Harry Potter craze swept the American coast.
In June, the U.S. publisher of the Harry Potter series rushed the hardcover edition of Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets onto bookstore shelves.
The institution also published the third book of the series, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban, and the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone on September 8.
By the end of that month, Rowling's novels had dominated the New York Times Best Sellers list, with the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone topping the paperback sales chart.
Time even put this bespectacled wizard on its cover.
The image of Harry Potter can be seen everywhere.
My students could not wait to find out what had caused such a frenzy.
Wow, they were utterly disappointed.
To them, the Harry Potter series was nothing but second-rate nonsense, unworthy of comparison to classics like The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings that they cherished from their childhood.
Though only a few years had passed since their childhood, they criticized Harry Potter as many notorious adult critics did: "plodding," "poorly written," "predictable," and "irritating."
Wow, they were utterly disappointed. To them, the Harry Potter series was nothing but second-rate nonsense, unworthy of comparison to classics like The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings that they cherished from their childhood. Though only a few years had passed since their childhood, they criticized Harry Potter as many notorious adult critics did: "plodding," "poorly written," "predictable," and "irritating."
To them, Harry lacked both wonder and wit and warmth.
The students' disdain surprised me, but in retrospect, there was nothing particularly remarkable about it.
Although adults constituted a significant portion of the Harry Potter audience from the beginning, these students were precisely in the wrong age bracket to objectively appreciate the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They were past the age of readily accepting new children's literature, yet still too young to have their own children (I had just become a parent myself), and they eagerly insisted that while the Harry Potter series was currently all the rage, it would soon be forgotten.
The following year in autumn, 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" as their term-end analysis book, just like their predecessors, confidently rejecting the work.
Let's fast-forward to spring 2007.
After suspending the course for a few years, I resumed teaching "Bestsellers in America".
When students chose their term-end analysis book, they selected "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone".
And I was ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
These were new-generation students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first encountered Rowling's works not as college students but as teenagers in their early teens. This meant they grew up alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
The same thing happened in autumn 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto rather than a label.
Will Harry disappear from memory?
As long as we are alive, it is impossible.
Since 2010, I have taught the bestseller course twice, and on both occasions, the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their term-end review.
Is it because they are tired of Potter?
Based on the context and previous translations, the English translation of the given Chinese source sentence is:
Now I choose to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but not "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone"; instead, I chose "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban" — which is my favorite among the seven novels in the series and marks the transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, depicting complex themes of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also love this book.
But how long will the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Each time I teach children's literature, I conduct a survey: "Which books from the大纲中列出的list have you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban".
In 2012, the percentage increased to 94%.
But the percentage continued to decline in subsequent years — 87% in 2014, and dropped to 81% in 2016.
These are not science, I know.
But I wonder: will the percentage of those who have read Harry Potter drop below 80% when I teach "Children's Literature" next spring?
Could the students of 1999-2000 be right, that Harry Potter's status is continually declining and it will never become a classic work that endures?
Is there still a balance point where the percentage can stabilize without continuing to decline?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us.
Until then, I was happy to continue inviting him into my classroom.
